		<credit project="CfPBoK@https://slebok.github.io/cfpbok/"/>
		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2025"></a><br><code>sle2025/paper08</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2025</a> paper:</span><br><i>AnyText: Incremental, left-recursive Parsing and Pretty-Printing from a single Grammar Definition with first-class LSP support</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/GeorgHinkel.html">Georg Hinkel</a>, <a href="../profile/AlexanderHert.html">Alexander Hert</a>, <a href="../profile/NiklasHettler.html">Niklas Hettler</a>, <a href="../profile/KevinWeinert.html">Kevin Weinert</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3732771.3742716">10.1145/3732771.3742716</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> AnyText is presented as a language workbench with first-class LSP support and integrated infrastructure.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> Its key technical contribution is incremental parsing (including left recursion) and pretty-print generation from grammar definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The central artifact is an EBNF-like grammar and extensions, i.e., a meta-language used to derive parsers/printers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
